 <text>
  <front>
   <head>To Mrs. Frances-Arabella Kelly.</head>
  </front>
  <body>
   <lg xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="poem">
    <lg n="1" stanza_type="couplet">
     <l n="1" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Day, as at my Glass I stood,</l>
     <l n="2" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">To set my Head-cloaths, and my Hood;</l>
     <l n="3" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">I saw my grizzled Locks with Dread,</l>
     <l n="4" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">And call'd to mind the  Head.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="2" stanza_type="couplet">
     <l n="5" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">I, whate'er the Poets say,</l>
     <l n="6" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Hair was only gray:</l>
     <l n="7" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Tho' , who the Story told,</l>
     <l n="8" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Was too well-bred to call her old;</l>
     <l n="9" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">But, what amounted to the same,</l>
     <l n="10" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">He made her an immortal Dame.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="3" stanza_type="couplet">
     <l n="11" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">now, whene'er a Matron sage</l>
     <l n="12" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Hath felt the rugged Hand of Age,</l>
     <l n="13" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">You hear out witty Coxcombs cry,</l>
     <l n="14" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8" />
     <l n="15" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Tho', had they but a little Reading,</l>
     <l n="16" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">would teach them better Breeding.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="4" stanza_type="couplet">
     <l n="17" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">now, I hear you say,</l>
     <l n="18" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Grant Heav'n, my Locks may ne'er be gray!</l>
     <l n="19" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Why am I told this frightful Story?</l>
     <l n="20" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">To Beauty a</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="5" stanza_type="couplet">
     <l n="21" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">, as along the Room you pass,</l>
     <l n="22" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Casting your Eye upon the Glass,</l>
     <l n="23" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Surely, say you, this lovely Face</l>
     <l n="24" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Will never suffer such Disgrace:</l>
     <l n="25" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">The Bloom, that on my Cheek appears,</l>
     <l n="26" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Will never be impair'd by Years.</l>
     <l n="27" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Her Envy, now, I plainly see,</l>
     <l n="28" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Makes her inscribe those Lines to me.</l>
     <l n="29" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">These Beldams, who were born before me,</l>
     <l n="30" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Are griev'd to see the Men adore me:</l>
     <l n="31" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Their snaky Locks freeze up the Blood;</l>
     <l n="32" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">My Tresses fire the purple Flood.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="6" stanza_type="couplet">
     <l n="33" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Slaves around me wait,</l>
     <l n="34" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">And from my Eyes expect their Fate:</l>
     <l n="35" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">I own, of Conquest I am vain,</l>
     <l n="36" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Tho' I despise the Slaves I gain.</l>
     <l n="37" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Heav'n gave me Charms, and destin'd me</l>
     <l n="38" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">For universal Tyranny.</l>
    </lg>
   </lg>
